The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the attempt by the Polish government to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Minister of Foreign Affairs - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another declaration stating that he was not a secret police agent at the time of communism.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government and Geremek stated that the law on lustration [décommunisation] constitutes a threat to public liberties.
In response, the Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and stirring up anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A decision by the constitutional court dated May 11 has largely invalidated the law on lustration, allowing Geremek to keep his seat in the European Parliament, at least for the time being.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government, which has no other goal than to weaken institutions and the democratic fabric of the country.
What is happening in Poland, a country where the collapse of communism began?
Each revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is a liberation of the human soul by which man expresses the best in him, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, avarice, suspicion, and the desire for vengeance.
The revolution triggered by the Polish Solidarity union followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced to clandestinity when martial law was decreed in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in broad daylight in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika".
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that opened the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a divided country between the all-powerful winners and the oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revanchards, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs of pre-war chauvinism, and the surroundings of radio Maryja, a mouthpiece for ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
We see alarming signs everywhere: the authority of Justice is eroded, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is questioned, officials are bought, and the role of the prosecutor is politicized.
Social life is subject to repressive regulation every day.
Why all this?
Every revolution that succeeds has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public liberties, but also more delinquency, a market economy as well as the risk of bankruptcy for companies and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced the fear of the stranger and the fear of a mass invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom is accompanied by many uncertainties.
In large corporations, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have conquered.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered as belonging to the state, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It's in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished, and the virtuous militants of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Moreover, the feeling of injustice gave birth to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed as much against the old enemies as against the old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to recognize that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would make crimes unpunished, virtue rewarded, and injustices redressed.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a great purge.
According to the first estimates, lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised to lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.

The Cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism, a cardinal has used such strong words.
Should this cleansing have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The purpose of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, for having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Polands are facing each other.
Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from clandestinity and prison - must prevail.
I believe that Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The court's constitutional decision leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will neither destroy the thing that gave it birth, the will for freedom, nor the thing it has engendered, a democratic state.
